Introduction~


The Reference section contains detailed information about PE II,
including all of its commands.



Internal Files~


Personal Editor II (PE II) has three internal files: the .KEYDEFS
file, the .UNNAMED file, and the .DIR file.  These files are
generated inside PE II.  They provide information you can use
when editing.

o  The .KEYDEFS file holds the current key definitions.

o  The .UNNAMED file holds the last five changes you made to
   active files.  You can specify that it hold up to ten
   changes.

o  The .DIR file gives the name, byte size, date, and the time
   the DOS files were last edited for any drive or subdirectory.

You use the EDIT command to see the .KEYDEFS file and the
.UNNAMED file.  You use the DIR command to see the .DIR file.

All internal files:

o  Become active files when displayed on the screen

o  Use a part of available memory

o  Let you mark and move text to another file where it can
   be saved

o  Require a valid filename if you use the SAVE or FILE
   command

o  Are removed from memory with the QUIT command


