Restoring Erased or Changed Text~


You can retrieve erased or changed text using either the UNDO
command or the .UNNAMED file.



Using the UNDO Command~


The UNDO command recovers a lost line of text.  It is initially
assigned to the Shift-F4 keys when you start PE II.  It restores
a line to the way it appeared before the cursor was moved to it,
even if it was previously blank.

UNDO restores characters that were erased or changed by:

o  Using the DELETE CHAR command (Del key)
o  Inserting or replacing characters
o  Using the ERASE END LINE command (F5 or F6)
o  Using the ERASE BEGIN LINE command

UNDO will not restore lines that were deleted with the DELETE
LINE command (Ctrl-Backspace), the DELETE MARK command (Alt-D),
or words that were erased by a series of commands assigned to a
key.

Once the cursor leaves the line that you have changed, you cannot
use the UNDO to recover the original line.  The cursor must
remain on the changed line to recover the text.



Using the .UNNAMED File~


You can also recover text by using the .UNNAMED file.  It allows
you to recover text even though the cursor has left the current
line.

The .UNNAMED file is the PE II internal file that holds the last
five changes you made to active files.  You can change this
number by using the SET BACKUP command.

If you change a line in one active file, then make single changes
in four other active files, the .UNNAMED file shows all five
changes.  If you make one more change, the first of the five
changes is removed from the .UNNAMED file.  The five changes are
separated by blank lines.

If you move too many marked lines, you may get a memory full
condition because of the space required in the .UNNAMED file to
hold the change.  To avoid this, use the SET BACKUP command to
change the number of groups of lines saved in the .UNNAMED file
to a lower number.



                                3


The following is a list of the types of changes or deletions that
appear in the .UNNAMED file:

o  Paragraphs before you used the paragraph Reflow command

o  Truncated lines that went past the right column limit of 255

o  A one-space block shift (each block shift is a single change
   to the .UNNAMED file)

o  Changed sentences up until the line had to split to fit into
   the margin settings

o  Deleted lines

o  All global and individual changes with the CHANGE command

o  Deletions using the RUBOUT command (Backspace key)

o  The same changes or deletions covered in the UNDO command

Quitting the .UNNAMED file erases its contents.  To keep its
contents, use F8 (Switch Files).



The Personal Editor II Profile~


When you start PE II, it reads a profile called PE2.PRO which
assigns the initial key definitions to the keyboard.  These
definitions are listed in the section "Default Profile
Definitions" in this document.



Converting PE Profiles to PE II Profiles~


PE profiles are compatible with PE II, with three exceptions:

o  The name PE.PRO must be renamed to PE2.PRO.  When you start PE
   II, it searches only for PE2.PRO, unless you specify another
   profile with the /p option, for example:

       pe2 /ppe.pro

o  Any instance of DOWN4, LEFT8, LEFT40, RIGHT8, RIGHT40, or UP4
   must be converted to DOWN 4, LEFT 8, LEFT 40, RIGHT 8,
   RIGHT 40, and UP 4.  This is to allow the specification of
   any numbers up to 16,300 in these commands.

o  Macros using [tab word] and [backtab word] may not work, since
   the meanings of those commands have changed.



