Changing Key Definitions~


The .KEYDEFS file displays the current key definitions.  Because
it is an internal file, you can only edit (display) it when you
are in PE II.

Each time you start using PE II, the PE2.PRO file and the
.KEYDEFS file contain the same key definitions. The .KEYDEFS file
lists all the possible key definitions in the long form.  The
PE2.PRO file lists the PE II key definitions that are not already
defined internally in the abbreviated form.  Both the .KEYDEFS
and PE2.PRO file should produce the same key definitions when
starting PE II.  You can temporarily change the definition of a
key by entering on the command line the DEFINE command followed
by the keyname and the new definition, (for example, def enter =
[insert line]).

You can also assign ASCII characters to keys, for example, the
square root symbol to Alt-4.  The square root symbol is the ASCII
character for the number 251.  See the IBM BASIC manual for a
list of ASCII characters and the decimal numbers for each.

After temporarily changing a key to a new definition, you may
find that you want to save it.  Saving a new definition makes it
unnecessary to retype the DEFINE command each time you start PE
II.

You can permanently change key definitions by either saving the
.KEYDEFS file under a new name or by changing the PE2.PRO file.



Saving the .KEYDEFS File Under a New Name~


In the Learning section, you assigned the INSERT LINE command to
the Enter key using the DEFINE command. The change was temporary
because you didn't save it.  Temporary changes are erased when
you exit PE II.

You can change the same key definition by editing the .KEYDEFS
file and typing the new key definition in the file.  Since the
.KEYDEFS file is an internal file, you cannot save it. However,
you can save a copy of the changes to another file, such as PE
II's profile.  On the command line, for example, you can type
SAVE PE2.PRO.  The changes are now saved to the file and can be
activated by either exiting PE II and starting the program again,
or by using the MACRO command on the command line (for example,
MACRO PE2.PRO).

    Note:  If you choose to activate the new definitions
    by restarting PE II, you should save the .KEYDEFS file
    to the filename PE2.PRO or use the /p option along with
    the filename to which you saved the .KEYDEFS file.

    If you save .KEYDEFS as PE2.PRO, you need to reenter
    your SET commands, such as margin settings.


                                5


Changing the PE2.PRO File~


You can also save a changed key definition by editing the PE2.PRO
file and saving it. The new key definitions can be activated by
restarting PE II or using the MACRO command along with the
filename.

     Note: You should not change the filename, PE2.PRO.
     PE II looks for a file called PE2.PRO when it starts.
     If you do change the profile name, you must use the
     /p option along with the profile when restarting PE II.

You can create a completely new profile for a special use.  You
could type the special key definitions in the .KEYDEFS file,
rename the file, and then save it.  Then, when you wanted to use
the special profile, you would type the MACRO command and the new
filename on the command line or use the /p option with the new
profile when starting PE II.

If you wanted the original profile of PE II, you would then type
the MACRO command and PE2.PRO.

You can make as many profiles as you need. For example, profiles
could be designed to help you type a structured programming
language, to keep facts and figures, or to type memos or personal
letters.



Macros~


A macro is a command or group of commands that are assigned to do
a task.  Pressing a key activates the macro defined to that key.
The MACRO command activates a macro file.  As you become familiar
with how commands work, individually or together, you can combine
them to do the task you want.

The PE2.PRO file is an example of a macro file.  Each time it is
activated, whether it is at the start of a program or by the
MACRO command, each command is executed line by line in the order
it appears in the file.  This is as if you entered each command
in the PE2.PRO file one line at a time.

For more information on building macros and macro files, see the
DEFINE and MACRO commands in the "Commands" section of this
document.


