Demonstration Mode~


PE II can demonstrate the actions of each of its commands or
macros automatically.  The DEMO FAST command allows the user to
see the action of each keystroke of a macro immediately, without
waiting for the entire macro or key definition to complete.

The DEMO SLOW command is similar, but inserts a short delay
between each automatic keystroke so that the operation of a macro
can better be observed.

Use the DEMO END command to tu n off demonstration mode.

By using these commands, as well as the split screen feature, you
can build demonstrations and tutorials.

You can also use the demonstration mode to debug keystroke
macros.  Suppose you have assigned a complicated key definition
to key c-f1.  The command "[demo slow] [key c-f1] [demo end]"
executes the actions of the key c-f1 slowly enough for you to
understand how it works (or fails to work).



DOS Path Support~


PE II allows DOS path names (including drive letters) to be used
in all commands requiring filenames.  A backward slash (\) is
used as the path delimiter.

PE II parses relative path names according to the current
directory and always displays full path names in the filename
field on the status line.  For example, if the current directory
is \level1\level2 and the command "e ..\new" is given, the
filename that PE II displays is "\level1\new."

You can use the CHDIR (CHANGE DIRECTORY) command to change the
current directory, as well as the default drive.



IBM TopView Support~


IBM TopView provides a multitasking and windowing environment for
software applications that run on several of the IBM Personal
Computers.

PE II can be run in the foreground of IBM TopView in normal mode.
To run PE II in the background, use the /b option when starting
PE II, which forces it to use BIOS for all screen output.

PE II requires a minimum of 112KB of memory.  You may want to

                                7

choose the Change Program Information option in TopView to
increase the maximum bytes of memory.  This gives PE II more edit
space before it must create a spill file.

PE II does not support TopView's cut and paste options.


