Storage and Memory Considerations~


PE II operations make use of available memory.  You need to
consider your IBM PC memory size when you use PE II. If you load
more bytes of text into memory than your system can hold, these
extra bytes "spill" back out to the disk.  However, you can still
edit these files.

The following require memory:

o  The number of active files in memory at one time
o  The number of lines in a file
o  Bringing in new files to be edited, including internal files
o  Using marked text
o  Copying and shifting lines
o  Adding or inserting lines
o  The number of commands assigned to keys in the PE2.PRO file



Disk Spill~


When you use all the available memory, PE II uses the default
drive as a place to store more information. Once a disk spill is
created on a diskette drive, the diskette cannot be removed from
the drive until the current session of PE II has ended.  At this
time, the spill file is erased.

Five important concepts about the disk spill process are:

o  Disk spill occurs automatically when PE II requires more
   memory than is available.  No text is lost.

o  PE II creates a temporary file called PE2TMP.nnn on the
   diskette to hold additional information from active files.
   The extension .nnn is a random number.  If more than one spill
   file is created, the names will be    unique.

o  The PE2TMP.nnn file can take up to 512KB of space on your disk
   if there is adequate space on the disk.

o  PE II always requires a minimum amount of memory to operate.

o  PE II performs quickest when all files are able to fit into
   memory--retrieving from and putting information on the disk
   requires more time than doing the same within memory.


                                9


PE II automatically creates the PE2TMP.nnn file when you either
load a file that is too big for memory or when you do text
editing that fills the available memory, such as copying lines.
When this happens, the message "Spill file created" appears on
the status line.  Do not remove a spill file diskette.

The PE2TMP.nnn spill file can be up to 512KB long, if there is
enough room on your disk. If you have less than 512KB free space
on your disk, the spill file will use what is available. The
PE2TMP.nnn file is like any other file in that it takes up space
on the disk.

PE II constantly uses memory.  When it needs more memory than is
available, it writes a block of lines from an active file to the
spill file. It then uses that memory space freed up by the
transfer to operate normally.

If you check your memory with the ? MEMORY command during the
spill disk condition, you will see that memory size remains about
the same.  It needs this minimum amount of memory to operate
normally.

When the spill file is filled, the message "Spill disk is full"
appears.   You then have only the minimum amount of memory
available.  When that is used up, PE II goes into a memory full
condition where you are restricted from normal operation.  This
is explained in the next section.


