Commands~


PE II commands are listed alphabetically in this section.
Parameters are separated from the command and from each other by
blanks. Optional parameters are shown within angle brackets < >.
You can type commands in uppercase or lowercase, or in a mixture
of cases.

At the end of each description are related commands.

In PE II there is little distinction between functions and
commands.  Any command can be assigned to a key with the DEFINE
command.  For example, you can assign the memory command (?
MEMORY) to the Alt-F1 key combination by entering the following
on the command line:

  def a-f1 = [? memory]

You must include the square brackets when using the DEFINE
command or building a macro.

You can also type function names (such as Reflow) directly on the
command line. The square brackets [ ] are optional, but it is
recommended that you use them. If brackets are not used, any
command beginning with a C or L will be treated as a CHANGE or
LOCATE command.

You can abbreviate all commands except for the SAVE, FILE, ERASE,
RENAME, DIR, LINE, COLUMN, DOWN, UP, LEFT, RIGHT, SCROLLUP,
SCROLLDOWN, SCROLLLEFT, SCROLLRIGHT, and nine SET commands.
These must be spelled out in full, although the word "set"
itself can be abbreviated to "s." Refer to the section "Command
Abbreviations" in this Reference document for abbreviations.

There are also a set of pseudo "keys" intended only for use
within complex macro definitions.  In addition to the unshifted
state, alphabetic shift (s-), control shift (c-), and alternate
shift (a-) provided in PE II, for each of the 76 definable keys
on the keyboard, PE II allows the user shift, indicated by the
prefix u-.  For example, if two key definitions shared a long
common expression, the common part could be assigned to the "key"
u-f1 and used from within the main key definitions using [key
u-f1].  You can invoke the user shift keys directly from the
command line by typing [key u-f1].

Some of the following command syntax shows characters between
angle brackets, such as LINE <nnnn>, where nnnn is a number which
you provide.  Do not type the angle brackets when using the
command.  They are there only to show that the characters between
them are optional.  For example, the command above could be
specified by LINE, LINE 1, LINE 724, or LINE 4682.


