Command Line Parameters~


When you start PE II from DOS by entering "PE2" at the DOS
prompt, you can also enter a series of options (command line
parameters) beginning with a slash (/) and separated from one
another by one or more blanks.

The letter after the slash specifies which command line option is
being set. The order of command options on the command line is
not significant.  If a command line option appears more than
once, PE II uses the last (rightmost) value.  The last command
line parameter not beginning with a slash, if any, is used as the
initial file to be read and displayed.

Command line parameters are:

/B

    The BIOS option forces PE II to use BIOS for all screen
    output.  This greatly slows PE II down, but BIOS
    compatibility may be required when running in certain
    environments.

/Pprofilename

    The profilename is processed as a file of PE II commands
    during editor initialization.  The default for this parameter
    is "/Ppe2.pro."  If PE II cannot find the named file, it uses
    an internal table as its profile.

/Rnnn

    Reserves nnn thousand bytes of random access memory for
    secondary copies of the DOS command interpreter.  Since
    PE II compresses its storage before loading a secondary
    command interpreter, it is hardly ever necessary to use this
    parameter.  The default (and minimum) value for this
    parameter is "/R2."

/Sspillfilename

    If PE II requires more storage than is available in random
    access memory, it dumps some of its internal data structures
    to the disk file named by this parameter.  The default for
    this parameter is "/Spe2tmp."  The filename extension is
    provided by PE II.

/Q

    The command line option /Q (quiet) tells PE II not to display
    its logo screen.

/W

    The command line option /W tells PE II to wait for a
    keystroke before reading the profile.  This allows you to
    change diskettes before PE II looks for the profile.


