CHANGE~

________________________________________

CHANGE replaces a character or string of
characters with another string.
_______________________________________

The CHANGE command searches from the current cursor position for
the first occurrence of a string, unless specified otherwise.

Format:  change/old/new/<-><*><m>

The CHANGE command consists of the keyword CHANGE (which may be
abbreviated to C), zero or more blanks, a nonblank delimiter
character, the search string, the delimiter, the replacement
string, and a closing delimiter.  The closing delimiter may
optionally be followed by the modifier characters "-", "*", and
"m".  Any combination of the modifiers may be present, but they
must appear in the order just given.

Examples:

    c!old!new!
    c'old'new'
    c xoldxnewx-*m
    c /old//*
    c/ /x/-m

To selectively replace some strings, type the CHANGE command on
the command line (without the *) and press Enter.  PE II moves to
the first occurrence of the string past the current cursor
position.

To change that present string to the new string, you must confirm
the change with the CONFIRM CHANGE command, which is initially
defined to the Shift-F5 key.

After you replace the first string, the CHANGE command and the
two strings remain on the command line.  This allows you to
search for the next string without typing the command again.

You can use Ctrl-Break to stop the search of the CHANGE command.

A nonblank character (a delimiter) must follow each part of the
CHANGE command, the present string, and the new string for the
CHANGE command to work.  The CHANGE command reads the first
nonblank character after the "c" or "change" as the separator.
It may be a letter, number, or a character such as a parenthesis,
a plus sign, or a slash.  The same character must follow each
part of the command, and the character may not be part of either
the search string or replacement string.

The options in brackets may be present in any combination, but
must appear in the order shown.


                               18

To replace a string from the current cursor position to the end
of the file (a global change), type the asterisk (*) following
the second delimiter.  When you press Enter, PE II finds all
occurrences of the present string and replaces them with the new
string.

The optional minus sign in the CHANGE command controls the
direction of the search.  If you do not type a minus sign,
searching begins at the cursor and continues to the end of the
line, and then to the bottom of the file.  If you type the minus
sign, the search begins from the cursor and continues to the
beginning of the line and then to the top of the file.

The optional modifier "m" specifies that the search is to include
only the marked area of the current file, if any.

PE II ignores whether you type the search string in uppercase,
lowercase, or mixed case, if ? SEARCHCASE is set to ANY.  For
example, if you type the string /MiXeD/, PE II finds any of these
strings:  mixed, MIXED, or mIxEd.  To see the searchcase, enter
? SEARCHCASE on the command line.

You can use the SET SEARCHCASE command to control whether or not
case is respected in the CHANGE command searches.

PE II, however, does insert the replacement string exactly as you
type it, regardless of the ? SEARCHCASE.  If the new string is
MiXeD, it will appear in text the same way.

Here are some examples of how to use the CHANGE command:

Command           What It Does

c(xyz(abc(        Changes xyz to abc individually with a forward
                  search.  Use the CONFIRM CHANGE command to
                  replace and the EXECUTE command to repeat the
                  command.

c/xyz//*          Deletes all occurrences of xyz (by changing
                  them to the empty string) from the current
                  file position to the end of the file.

c!xyz! XYZ !-*    Capitalizes and puts spaces on both sides of
                  all occurrences of xyz from the cursor
                  position to the top of the file.

c'/*'(*'*         Changes all occurrences of /* to  (*  from the
                  current position to the end of the file.

c/abc/xyz/*m      Changes all occurrences of abc to xyz only in
                  the marked part of the file from the current
                  cursor.

See also CONFIRM CHANGE, LOCATE, SET SEARCHCASE, and
? SEARCHCASE.


