DOS~

________________________________________

DOS loads another copy of the command
interpreter into memory and allows
execution of any DOS program or command.
________________________________________

PE II squeezes all of its dynamic memory together, releases
any that remains to DOS, then invokes another copy of the command
interpreter (usually COMMAND.COM).  PE II uses the COMSPEC=
parameter of its environment to find the location of the command
interpreter.

Use the command ? MEMORY to see how much memory is available.
That amount of memory will be available to the secondary command
interpreter, although some of the memory will be used up to load
COMMAND.COM.  Therefore, the PE II ? MEMORY command and the DOS
CHKDSK commands will not give the same number for bytes of
available memory.  The secondary command interpreter can be used
to execute any DOS program or command.

To return to PE II, leave the command interpreter using the
special command EXIT.  PE II checksums all of its code and data
areas before and after the command interpreter runs to protect
itself against modification by programs run from the secondary
command interpreter.  If you change an active PE II file while in
DOS, you will need to reload the file to use the changed file
because PE II will not contain the changes when you exit to it.

Do not run programs in the secondary command interpreter that
remain resident because memory will not be given back to PE II
after returning with the EXIT command.





