UNMARK~

________________________________________

UNMARK removes the highlighting of any
currently marked areas.
________________________________________

UNMARK removes all marks that exist in any active file.  No
change occurs to the text inside of the marked area.

UNMARK will not affect marked areas saved on the stack.

Commands that operate on marked areas cannot be used after UNMARK
until a new marked area is defined.

See also CLEAR MARKS, MARK BLOCK, MARK CHAR, MARK LINE, PUSH
MARK, and POP MARK.







UP~

________________________________________

UP moves the cursor up the number of
lines specified.
________________________________________

Format:  up <nnnn>

where nnnn is the number of lines up you want to move the cursor.

If you do not specify a number, UP moves the cursor up one line.

The column of the cursor does not change.

If the cursor is at the top of the window but not at the top of
the file, the cursor remains stationary and the text in the
window shifts down by one line, bringing a new line into view.

If you use UP on the command line, the cursor moves to the bottom
line of the current window in the text area.

See also DOWN.


